[{"id":"VR914667","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows an electromagnetic wave pulse labeled vector E. The electromagnetic wave pulse is represented by a dashed curve that moves along a solid arrow that slants downward and to the right in a straight line. Ten evenly spaced arrows which originate on the solid arrow and terminate on the dashed curve, extend vertically upward from the slanted arrow to the dashed curve. The arrows are shorter toward the outside of the curve and longer toward the center of the curve.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR914667.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">An electromagnetic wave pulse, represented in the figure, consists of a pulse-shaped pattern of electric fields <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"vector E\"><math alttext=\"vector E\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mover><mi>E</mi><mo>â†’</mo></mover></math></span></span> that travels through space, with a speed equal to the speed of light in that medium. The pulse initially travels in a vacuum and is incident on a piece of glass with an index of refraction of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1.50\"><math alttext=\"1.50\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1.50</mn></math></span></span>. The pulse is then both reflected off the glass surface and transmitted into the glass. Which of the following correctly describes the energy carried by the transmitted pulse and the orientation of the reflected pulse?</p><div class=\"table_wrapper\"><table class=\"tgroup align:center cols:3 colsep:0 frame:none rowsep:0\"><col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col1 colnum:1 colsep:1 colwidth:30\"/><col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col2 colnum:2 colwidth:165\"/><col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col3 colnum:3 colwidth:170\"/><thead class=\"thead\"><tr class=\"row rowsep:1\"><th class=\"entry colname:col1\"></th><th class=\"entry colname:col2\">Energy of Transmitted Pulse</th><th class=\"entry colname:col3\">Orientation of Reflected Pulse</th></tr></thead><tbody class=\"tbody valign:middle\"><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">A</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Equal to that of the incident pulse.</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">The same as the incident pulse.</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">B</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Equal to that of the incident pulse.</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">Inverted relative to the incident pulse.</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">C</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Less than that of the incident pulse.</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">The same as the incident pulse.</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">D</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Less than that of the incident pulse.</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">Inverted relative to the incident pulse.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR914667_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">A</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">B</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">C</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">D</p>"],"answer":3}]